{"questionId":"28390","questionHtml":"<p>The centre of the Earth and the Moon are a distance <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>D</mi></math> apart. There is a point X between them where their gravitational fields cancel out. The distance from the centre of the Earth to X is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>d</mi></math>. The mass of the Earth is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>M</mi><mtext>E</mtext></msub></math> and the mass of the Moon is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>M</mi><mtext>M</mtext></msub></math>.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/9f59dc7f0a52342af3cfd2f5f87d25e23c7a2258.png\"></p>\n<p>What is correct at X?</p>\n<p><br>A.&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>M</mi><mtext>E</mtext></msub><mi>d</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>M</mi><mtext>M</mtext></msub><mrow><mi>D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>d</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p>\n<p>B.&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>M</mi><mtext>E</mtext></msub><mrow><mi>D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>d</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>M</mi><mtext>M</mtext></msub><mi>d</mi></mfrac></math></p>\n<p>C.&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>M</mi><mi>E</mi></msub><msup><mi>d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>M</mi><mtext>M</mtext></msub><msup><mfenced><mrow><mi>D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>d</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math></p>\n<p>D.&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>M</mi><mi>E</mi></msub><msup><mi>d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>M</mi><mtext>M</mtext></msub><mrow><msup><mi>D</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>C</p>","meta":{"questionId":"28390","referenceCode":"22N.1.SL.TZ0.22","subjectId":"46-dp-physics-last-assessment-2024","title":"The centre of the Earth and the Moon are a distance D apart. There is a point X between them where their gravitational fields cancel out. The distance from the centre of the Earth ","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"22","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Core","Core","Topic 6: Circular motion and gravitation","6.2 – Newton’s law of gravitation","Core","Topic 6: Circular motion and gravitation"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}